{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848440825,"sessionID":"ses_28730ac95ffeAn455E0f48zV8R","part":{"id":"prt_d78d0b00f001Nuck1k33jA5A9h","messageID":"msg_d78cff166001judkILCSG3ZaJA","sessionID":"ses_28730ac95ffeAn455E0f48zV8R","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:11","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-005/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-005/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Spec: AR-005 — Sandbox 创建处理器\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **AR ID:** AR-005  \n6: **Module:** `pkg/workloadmanager`  \n7: **Language:** Go  \n8: **Size:** M  \n9: \n10: Implement the Sandbox creation handler for the WorkloadManager that processes sandbox creation requests from `POST /v1/agent-runtime` and `POST /v1/code-interpreter`, provisions isolated execution environments for agents, and manages the lifecycle of sandbox resources. The handler integrates with the existing HTTP service framework (AR-004) and the generated client-go library (AR-003).\n11: \n12: ---\n13: \n14: ## Requirements\n15: \n16: ### Requirement: AgentRuntime Sandbox Creation Endpoint\n17: \n18: The system SHALL expose an HTTP endpoint to create sandboxes from AgentRuntime workload definitions.\n19: \n20: #### Scenario: Create sandbox from valid AgentRuntime\n21: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime named `test-runtime` exists in namespace `default` with a valid pod template\n22: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/v1/agent-runtime` with body `{\"name\": \"test-runtime\", \"namespace\": \"default\"}`\n23: - **THEN** the server SHALL:\n24:   1. Validate the request (Kind=AgentRuntime, name and namespace non-empty)\n25:   2. Retrieve the AgentRuntime from informer cache\n26:   3. Build a Sandbox object with generated name `{workloadName}-{RandString(8)}`\n27:   4. Create placeholder in Store with status \"pending\"\n28:   5. Register watcher before creating CR to avoid race conditions\n29:   6. Create the Sandbox CR via dynamic client\n30:   7. Wait up to 2 minutes for Sandbox to reach \"running\" status\n31:   8. Resolve Pod IP and build entryPoints from spec.Ports\n32:   9. Update Store with full SandboxInfo including entryPoints\n33:   10. Return HTTP 200 with `CreateSandboxResponse` containing sessionId and entryPoints\n34: \n35: #### Scenario: Create sandbox with missing pod template\n36: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime named `invalid-runtime` exists in namespace `default` with `spec.template=nil`\n37: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/v1/agent-runtime` with body `{\"name\": \"invalid-runtime\", \"namespace\": \"default\"}`\n38: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 with message containing \"pod template\"\n39: \n40: #### Scenario: Create sandbox for non-existent AgentRuntime\n41: - **GIVEN** no AgentRuntime named `missing-runtime` exists in namespace `default`\n42: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/v1/agent-runtime` with body `{\"name\": \"missing-runtime\", \"namespace\": \"default\"}`\n43: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 404 with message \"agent runtime not found\"\n44: \n45: #### Scenario: Create sandbox with invalid request body\n46: - **GIVEN** a malformed JSON payload\n47: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/v1/agent-runtime` with invalid JSON\n48: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 with message \"Invalid request body\"\n49: \n50: #### Scenario: Create sandbox with missing required fields\n51: - **GIVEN** a request missing the `name` field\n52: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/v1/agent-runtime` with body `{\"namespace\": \"default\"}`\n53: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 with message \"name is required\"\n54: \n55: #### Scenario: Create sandbox with missing namespace\n56: - **GIVEN** a request missing the `namespace` field\n57: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/v1/agent-runtime` with body `{\"name\": \"test-runtime\"}`\n58: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 with message \"namespace is required\"\n59: \n60: ---\n61: \n62: ### Requirement: CodeInterpreter Sandbox Creation Endpoint\n63: \n64: The system SHALL expose an HTTP endpoint to create sandboxes from CodeInterpreter workload definitions.\n65: \n66: #### Scenario: Create sandbox from valid CodeInterpreter\n67: - **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter named `test-interpreter` exists in namespace `default` with valid template\n68: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/v1/code-interpreter` with body `{\"name\": \"test-interpreter\", \"namespace\": \"default\"}`\n69: - **THEN** the server SHALL:\n70:   1. Validate the request (Kind=CodeInterpreter, name and namespace non-empty)\n71:   2. Retrieve the CodeInterpreter from informer cache\n72:   3. Build a Sandbox or SandboxClaim object based on WarmPoolSize\n73:   4. Apply default ports `[{Port: 8080, Protocol: \"HTTP\", PathPrefix: \"/\"}]` if spec.Ports is empty\n74:   5. Inject `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` env var if AuthMode=picod and publicKey is available\n75:   6. Follow the same creation and wait flow as AgentRuntime\n76:   7. Return HTTP 200 with `CreateSandboxResponse`\n77: \n78: #### Scenario: Create SandboxClaim for warm pool\n79: - **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter named `warm-interpreter` exists with `WarmPoolSize > 0`\n80: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/v1/code-interpreter`\n81: - **THEN** the server SHALL create a `SandboxClaim` (not full Sandbox) with Kind=\"SandboxClaim\"\n82: \n83: #### Scenario: Create full Sandbox for non-warm pool\n84: - **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter named `cold-interpreter` exists with `WarmPoolSize=0` or unset\n85: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/v1/code-interpreter`\n86: - **THEN** the server SHALL create a full `Sandbox` with single container named `code-interpreter`\n87: \n88: #### Scenario: Create sandbox for non-existent CodeInterpreter\n89: - **GIVEN** no CodeInterpreter named `missing-interpreter` exists\n90: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/v1/code-interpreter` with body `{\"name\": \"missing-interpreter\", \"namespace\": \"default\"}`\n91: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 404 with message \"code interpreter not found\"\n92: \n93: ---\n94: \n95: ### Requirement: Sandbox Object Building\n96: \n97: The system SHALL build proper Sandbox/SandboxClaim objects from workload definitions.\n98: \n99: #### Scenario: Build Sandbox object with correct metadata\n100: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime with name `my-runtime` and a sessionID `sess-123`\n101: - **WHEN** `buildSandboxObject()` is called\n102: - **THEN** the resulting Sandbox SHALL have:\n103:   - Name: `my-runtime-{8-char-random}`\n104:   - APIVersion: `agents.x-k8s.io/v1alpha1`\n105:   - Kind: `Sandbox`\n106:   - Labels:\n107:     - `runtime.agentcube.io/session-id`: sessionID\n108:     - `runtime.agentcube.io/workload-name`: runtime.Name\n109:     - `runtime.agentcube.io/sandbox-name`: sandboxName\n110:     - `managed-by`: `agentcube-workload-manager`\n111:   - Annotations:\n112:     - `runtime.agentcube.io/idle-timeout`: SessionTimeout (default \"15m\")\n113: \n114: #### Scenario: Build Sandbox with lifecycle settings\n115: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime with `MaxSessionDuration` set to 8 hours\n116: - **WHEN** `buildSandboxObject()` is called\n117: - **THEN** the Sandbox spec SHALL include `lifecycle.shutdownTime` set to `now + MaxSessionDuration`\n118: \n119: #### Scenario: Build CodeInterpreter Sandbox with auth mode\n120: - **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter with `AuthMode=picod` and a public key available\n121: - **WHEN** `buildSandboxObject()` is called\n122: - **THEN** the container SHALL have environment variable `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` set to the public key\n123: \n124: #### Scenario: Build CodeInterpreter Sandbox without auth\n125: - **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter with `AuthMode=none`\n126: - **WHEN** `buildSandboxObject()` is called\n127: - **THEN** the container SHALL NOT have `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` environment variable\n128: \n129: #### Scenario: Build SandboxClaim for warm pool\n130: - **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter with `WarmPoolSize=5`\n131: - **WHEN** `buildSandboxClaimObject()` is called\n132: - **THEN** the resulting object SHALL have:\n133:   - APIVersion: `extensions.agents.x-k8s.io/v1alpha1`\n134:   - Kind: `SandboxClaim`\n135:   - Minimal metadata (no full PodSpec)\n136: \n137: ---\n138: \n139: ### Requirement: Sandbox Creation and Wait Flow\n140: \n141: The system SHALL orchestrate the creation flow with proper synchronization and timeouts.\n142: \n143: #### Scenario: Register watcher before CR creation\n144: - **GIVEN** a Sandbox object ready to be created\n145: - **WHEN** `createSandbox()` is invoked\n146: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `WatchSandboxOnce()` to register the watcher BEFORE calling `dynamicClient.Create()`\n147: \n148: #### Scenario: Store placeholder before CR creation\n149: - **GIVEN** a Sandbox object ready to be created\n150: - **WHEN** `createSandbox()` is invoked\n151: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `StoreSandbox()` with status \"pending\" BEFORE creating the CR\n152: \n153: #### Scenario: Successfully wait for sandbox running\n154: - **GIVEN** a Sandbox CR has been created\n155: - **WHEN** the SandboxReconciler notifies the sandbox is running within 2 minutes\n156: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n157:   1. Receive notification from the watcher channel\n158:   2. Resolve Pod IP using `resolvePodIP()`\n159:   3. Build entryPoints from ports and Pod IP\n160:   4. Update Store with status \"running\" and entryPoints\n161:   5. Return the complete SandboxInfo\n162: \n163: #### Scenario: Timeout waiting for sandbox running\n164: - **GIVEN** a Sandbox CR has been created but does not reach running state\n165: - **WHEN** 2 minutes elapse without receiving running notification\n166: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n167:   1. Cancel the wait context\n168:   2. Delete the CR with a 30-second timeout context\n169:   3. Delete the Store placeholder\n170:   4. Return error \"sandbox creation timed out\"\n171: \n172: #### Scenario: Pod IP resolution from annotation\n173: - **GIVEN** a running Sandbox with annotation `agents.x-k8s.io/sandbox-pod-name=my-pod`\n174: - **WHEN** `resolvePodIP()` is called\n175: - **THEN** the system SHALL first check the annotation and use `my-pod` as the pod name to look up\n176: \n177: #### Scenario: Pod IP resolution from owner reference\n178: - **GIVEN** a running Sandbox without pod name annotation\n179: - **WHEN** `resolvePodIP()` is called\n180: - **THEN** the system SHALL list pods by label `runtime.agentcube.io/sandbox-name` and select the one with OwnerReference matching the Sandbox\n181: \n182: #### Scenario: Pod IP resolution failure\n183: - **GIVEN** no running pod exists for the sandbox\n184: - **WHEN** `resolvePodIP()` is called\n185: - **THEN** the system SHALL return error \"no running pod found for sandbox {name}\"\n186: \n187: ---\n188: \n189: ### Requirement: Rollback and Cleanup\n190: \n191: The system SHALL implement proper rollback on creation failures.\n192: \n193: #### Scenario: Rollback on CR creation failure\n194: - **GIVEN** Store placeholder has been created\n195: - **WHEN** dynamic client Create() fails\n196: - **THEN** the system SHALL delete the Store placeholder using `DeleteSandboxBySessionID()`\n197: \n198: #### Scenario: Rollback on timeout\n199: - **GIVEN** CR has been created but sandbox never reaches running\n200: - **WHEN** timeout occurs after 2 minutes\n201: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n202:   1. Delete the CR using dynamic client with 30s timeout\n203:   2. Delete the Store placeholder\n204:   3. Return timeout error\n205: \n206: #### Scenario: Rollback on Pod IP resolution failure\n207: - **GIVEN** CR has been created and sandbox is running\n208: - **WHEN** Pod IP resolution fails\n209: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n210:   1. Delete the CR\n211:   2. Delete the Store placeholder\n212:   3. Return resolution error\n213: \n214: #### Scenario: Handle Store update failure\n215: - **GIVEN** CR is created and running, Pod IP is resolved\n216: - **WHEN** `UpdateSandbox()` fails\n217: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n218:   1. Log warning about Store inconsistency\n219:   2. CR will be eventually cleaned up by GC\n220:   3. Return the error\n221: \n222: ---\n223: \n224: ### Requirement: Request Validation\n225: \n226: The system SHALL validate CreateSandboxRequest according to defined rules.\n227: \n228: #### Scenario: Validate valid request\n229: - **GIVEN** a CreateSandboxRequest with `Kind=\"AgentRuntime\"`, `Name=\"test\"`, `Namespace=\"default\"`\n230: - **WHEN** `Validate()` is called\n231: - **THEN** the method SHALL return nil (no error)\n232: \n233: #### Scenario: Validate rejects empty name\n234: - **GIVEN** a CreateSandboxRequest with empty `Name` field\n235: - **WHEN** `Validate()` is called\n236: - **THEN** the method SHALL return error with message \"name is required\"\n237: \n238: #### Scenario: Validate rejects empty namespace\n239: - **GIVEN** a CreateSandboxRequest with empty `Namespace` field\n240: - **WHEN** `Validate()` is called\n241: - **THEN** the method SHALL return error with message \"namespace is required\"\n242: \n243: #### Scenario: Validate rejects invalid kind\n244: - **GIVEN** a CreateSandboxRequest with `Kind=\"InvalidKind\"`\n245: - **WHEN** `Validate()` is called\n246: - **THEN** the method SHALL return error with message \"kind is required\" (or invalid kind)\n247: \n248: ---\n249: \n250: ### Requirement: Response Building\n251: \n252: The system SHALL build proper CreateSandboxResponse from SandboxInfo.\n253: \n254: #### Scenario: Build response with entryPoints\n255: - **GIVEN** a SandboxInfo with:\n256:   - SessionID: `sess-abc-123`\n257:   - SandboxID: `runtime-xyz-789`\n258:   - SandboxName: `my-runtime-abcdef12`\n259:   - EntryPoints: `[{Path: \"/\", Protocol: \"HTTP\", Endpoint: \"10.244.0.5:8080\"}]`\n260: - **WHEN** building the HTTP response\n261: - **THEN** the response SHALL contain:\n262:   ```json\n263:   {\n264:     \"sessionId\": \"sess-abc-123\",\n265:     \"sandboxId\": \"runtime-xyz-789\",\n266:     \"sandboxName\": \"my-runtime-abcdef12\",\n267:     \"entryPoints\": [\n268:       {\n269:         \"path\": \"/\",\n270:         \"protocol\": \"HTTP\",\n271:         \"endpoint\": \"10.244.0.5:8080\"\n272:       }\n273:     ]\n274:   }\n275:   ```\n276: \n277: ---\n278: \n279: ### Requirement: Authentication Integration\n280: \n281: The system SHALL integrate with authentication middleware when enabled.\n282: \n283: #### Scenario: Extract auth context when auth enabled\n284: - **GIVEN** `EnableAuth=true` and request has valid Authorization header\n285: - **WHEN** the handler processes the request\n286: - **THEN** the context SHALL contain:\n287:   - `contextKeyUserToken`: the bearer token\n288:   - `contextKeyServiceAccount`: the service account name\n289:   - `contextKeyNamespace`: the namespace for per-user client caching\n290: \n291: #### Scenario: Reject request without auth header\n292: - **GIVEN** `EnableAuth=true` and request has no Authorization header\n293: - **WHEN** authMiddleware processes the request\n294: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 401 with message \"Missing authorization header\"\n295: \n296: #### Scenario: Reject invalid token\n297: - **GIVEN** `EnableAuth=true` and request has invalid token\n298: - **WHEN** authMiddleware calls TokenReview\n299: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 401 with TokenReview error message\n300: \n301: #### Scenario: Use per-user client when auth enabled\n302: - **GIVEN** `EnableAuth=true` and auth context is present\n303: - **WHEN** creating the Sandbox CR\n304: - **THEN** the system SHALL use `GetOrCreateUserK8sClient()` to get per-user dynamic client\n305: \n306: ---\n307: \n308: ### Requirement: Idempotency\n309: \n310: The system SHALL support idempotent creation requests.\n311: \n312: #### Scenario: Return existing session for duplicate request\n313: - **GIVEN** a sandbox creation request for AgentRuntime `test-runtime` has already succeeded with sessionID `sess-123`\n314: - **WHEN** the same request is made again\n315: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n316:   1. Check Store for existing session by workload name\n317:   2. Return the existing sessionID without creating new sandbox\n318:   3. Return HTTP 200 with original CreateSandboxResponse\n319: \n320: ---\n321: \n322: ### Requirement: Error Handling and HTTP Status Mapping\n323: \n324: The system SHALL map internal errors to appropriate HTTP status codes.\n325: \n326: #### Scenario: Map JSON binding error to 400\n327: - **GIVEN** request body is malformed JSON\n328: - **WHEN** `c.ShouldBindJSON()` fails\n329: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 with message \"Invalid request body\"\n330: \n331: #### Scenario: Map validation error to 400\n332: - **GIVEN** request fails validation (missing required field)\n333: - **WHEN** `Validate()` returns error\n334: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 with validation error message\n335: \n336: #### Scenario: Map not found to 404\n337: - **GIVEN** AgentRuntime or CodeInterpreter is not found in informer cache\n338: - **WHEN** lookup fails\n339: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 404 with appropriate \"not found\" message\n340: \n341: #### Scenario: Map internal errors to 500\n342: - **GIVEN** an unexpected internal error occurs (Store failure, K8s API error)\n343: - **WHEN** error is processed\n344: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 500 with message \"internal server error\" (details logged but not exposed)\n345: \n346: #### Scenario: Map timeout to 500\n347: - **GIVEN** sandbox creation times out after 2 minutes\n348: - **WHEN** timeout occurs\n349: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 500 with message \"internal server error\"\n350: \n351: ---\n352: \n353: ### Requirement: Context Propagation\n354: \n355: The system SHALL properly propagate context through the creation flow.\n356: \n357: #### Scenario: Pass context through creation flow\n358: - **GIVEN** a request context with requestID and auth info\n359: - **WHEN** the creation flow executes (validate → build → create → wait)\n360: - **THEN** the context SHALL be passed to all operations for cancellation and timeout handling\n361: \n362: #### Scenario: Handle context cancellation during wait\n363: - **GIVEN** sandbox is waiting for running status\n364: - **WHEN** the parent context is cancelled (e.g., client disconnects)\n365: - **THEN** the wait SHALL be cancelled and resources cleaned up\n366: \n367: ---\n368: \n369: ### Requirement: Timeout Configuration\n370: \n371: The system SHALL enforce configurable timeouts for sandbox operations.\n372: \n373: #### Scenario: Enforce 2-minute creation timeout\n374: - **GIVEN** default timeout configuration\n375: - **WHEN** creating sandbox with `context.WithTimeout(ctx, 2*time.Minute)`\n376: - **THEN** the operation SHALL timeout after 2 minutes if sandbox doesn't reach running\n377: \n378: #### Scenario: Enforce 30-second deletion timeout on rollback\n379: - **GIVEN** rollback is triggered after creation timeout\n380: - **WHEN** deleting the CR\n381: - **THEN** the deletion SHALL use `context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 30*time.Second)`\n382: \n383: ---\n384: \n385: ## File Index\n386: \n387: | Path | Purpose |\n388: |------|---------|\n389: | `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers.go` | HTTP handlers: `handleAgentRuntimeCreate`, `handleCodeInterpreterCreate` |\n390: | `pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox_creator.go` | `sandboxCreator` struct and `createSandbox()` orchestration |\n391: | `pkg/workloadmanager/workload_builder.go` | `buildSandboxObject()`, `buildSandboxClaimObject()`, `resolvePodIP()`, `buildEntryPoints()` |\n392: | `pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox_controller.go` | `SandboxReconciler`, `WatchSandboxOnce()`, sandbox status tracking |\n393: | `pkg/workloadmanager/informers.go` | GVR definitions, `Informers` struct, informer lifecycle |\n394: | `pkg/workloadmanager/k8s_client.go` | `K8sClient`, `ClientCache`, `GetOrCreateUserK8sClient()` |\n395: | `pkg/workloadmanager/auth.go` | `authMiddleware`, context keys, token validation |\n396: | `pkg/workloadmanager/defaults.go` | Constants: `DefaultSandboxTTL`, `DefaultSandboxIdleTimeout`, label/annotation keys |\n397: | `pkg/workloadmanager/types/sandbox.go` | Sandbox domain types (if not in pkg/apis) |\n398: | `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers_test.go` | Handler unit tests |\n399: | `pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox_creator_test.go` | Sandbox creation flow tests |\n400: | `pkg/workloadmanager/workload_builder_test.go` | Object building tests |\n401: \n402: ---\n403: \n404: ## Dependencies\n405: \n406: | Dependency | Version | Purpose |\n407: |------------|---------|---------|\n408: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go` | Local | Generated Kubernetes clientset, informers, listers |\n409: | `k8s.io/client-go` | `v0.34.1` | Dynamic client, REST client |\n410: | `k8s.io/apimachinery` | `v0.34.1` | Kubernetes API machinery, unstructured |\n411: | `github.com/gin-gonic/gin` | Latest | HTTP framework (inherited from AR-004) |\n412: | `github.com/google/uuid` | Latest | UUID generation for sessionID |\n413: | `github.com/alicebob/miniredis/v2` | Latest | Test dependency for mock Redis |\n414: \n415: ---\n416: \n417: ## API Endpoints Summary\n418: \n419: | Method | Path | Description |\n420: |--------|------|-------------|\n421: | POST | `/v1/agent-runtime` | Create sandbox from AgentRuntime definition |\n422: | POST | `/v1/code-interpreter` | Create sandbox from CodeInterpreter definition |\n423: \n424: ---\n425: \n426: ## Data Types\n427: \n428: ### CreateSandboxRequest\n429: ```go\n430: type CreateSandboxRequest struct {\n431:     Kind      string `json:\"kind\"`      // \"AgentRuntime\" or \"CodeInterpreter\"\n432:     Name      string `json:\"name\"`      // workload name\n433:     Namespace string `json:\"namespace\"` // workload namespace\n434: }\n435: ```\n436: \n437: ### CreateSandboxResponse\n438: ```go\n439: type CreateSandboxResponse struct {\n440:     SessionID   string              `json:\"sessionId\"`\n441:     SandboxID   string              `json:\"sandboxId\"`\n442:     SandboxName string              `json:\"sandboxName\"`\n443:     EntryPoints []SandboxEntryPoint `json:\"entryPoints\"`\n444: }\n445: \n446: type SandboxEntryPoint struct {\n447:     Path     string `json:\"path\"`     // route path prefix\n448:     Protocol string `json:\"protocol\"` // \"HTTP\" or \"HTTPS\"\n449:     Endpoint string `json:\"endpoint\"` // \"host:port\"\n450: }\n451: ```\n452: \n453: ### SandboxInfo (Store model)\n454: ```go\n455: type SandboxInfo struct {\n456:     Kind             string                `json:\"kind\"`             // \"Sandbox\" or \"SandboxClaim\"\n457:     SandboxID        string                `json:\"sandboxId\"`\n458:     SandboxNamespace string                `json:\"sandboxNamespace\"`\n459:     Name             string                `json:\"name\"`\n460:     SessionID        string                `json:\"sessionId\"`\n461:     EntryPoints      []SandboxEntryPoint   `json:\"entryPoints\"`\n462:     Status           string                `json:\"status\"`           // \"pending\", \"running\", \"failed\"\n463:     CreatedAt        time.Time             `json:\"createdAt\"`\n464:     ExpiresAt        time.Time             `json:\"expiresAt\"`\n465: }\n466: ```\n467: \n468: ---\n469: \n470: ## Integration with client-go\n471: \n472: | Component | Usage |\n473: |-----------|-------|\n474: | `clientset/versioned.Interface` | Get typed client for AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter |\n475: | `informers/externalversions.SharedInformerFactory` | Informer lifecycle management |\n476: | `listers/runtime/v1alpha1.AgentRuntimeLister` | Read-only AgentRuntime queries |\n477: | `listers/runtime/v1alpha1.CodeInterpreterLister` | Read-only CodeInterpreter queries |\n478: | `fake.Clientset` | Unit test mocks |\n479: \n480: ---\n481: \n482: ## Notes\n483: \n484: - Watcher MUST be registered BEFORE creating the CR to avoid race conditions where Sandbox enters running before watcher is ready\n485: - Store placeholder MUST be created BEFORE CR creation for idempotency and rollback\n486: - Dynamic client is used for Sandbox/SandboxClaim CRDs (external to agentcube)\n487: - Per-user K8s client is used when authentication is enabled\n488: - All timeouts are configurable via constants in `defaults.go`\n489: - EntryPoints are built from `spec.Ports` with format: `{PathPrefix, Protocol, PodIP:Port}`\n\n(End of file - total 489 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Spec: AR-005 — Sandbox 创建处理器\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-005  \n**Module:** `pkg/workloadmanager`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n\nImplement the Sandbox creation handler for the WorkloadManager that processes sandbox creation requests from `POST /v1/agent-runtime` and `POST /v1/code-interpreter`, provisions isolated execution environments for agents, and manages the lifecycle of sandbox resources. The handler integrates with the existing HTTP service framework (AR-004) and the generated client-go library (AR-003).\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: AgentRuntime Sandbox Creation Endpoint\n\nThe system SHALL expose an HTTP endpoint to create sandboxes from AgentRuntime workload definitions.\n\n#### Scenario: Create sandbox from valid AgentRuntime","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-005/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775848440792,"end":1775848440823}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848440828,"sessionID":"ses_28730ac95ffeAn455E0f48zV8R","part":{"id":"prt_d78d0b892001BaoifsVPb4Mel4","messageID":"msg_d78cff166001judkILCSG3ZaJA","sessionID":"ses_28730ac95ffeAn455E0f48zV8R","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:12","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Spec: AR-004 — WorkloadManager HTTP Service Framework\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **AR ID:** AR-004  \n6: **Module:** pkg/workloadmanager  \n7: **Language:** Go  \n8: **Size:** M  \n9: \n10: Establish the HTTP service framework for the WorkloadManager component, providing RESTful APIs for managing AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources, health endpoints, and integration with the Kubernetes client-go library.\n11: \n12: ---\n13: \n14: ## Requirements\n15: \n16: ### Requirement: HTTP Server Bootstrap\n17: \n18: The system SHALL provide a configurable HTTP server that can be started and gracefully shut down.\n19: \n20: #### Scenario: Server starts with configuration\n21: - **GIVEN** a valid server configuration with host, port, and handler registrations\n22: - **WHEN** the operator calls `server.Start()`\n23: - **THEN** the HTTP server SHALL bind to the configured address and begin accepting connections\n24: \n25: #### Scenario: Server shuts down gracefully\n26: - **GIVEN** a running HTTP server with active connections\n27: - **WHEN** the operator calls `server.Shutdown(ctx)` with a context timeout\n28: - **THEN** the server SHALL stop accepting new connections, wait for existing requests to complete (within timeout), and release resources\n29: \n30: #### Scenario: Server configuration from environment\n31: - **GIVEN** environment variables `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_HOST` (default \"0.0.0.0\") and `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_PORT` (default \"8080\")\n32: - **WHEN** the operator initializes the server configuration\n33: - **THEN** the configuration SHALL read from these environment variables with sensible defaults\n34: \n35: #### Scenario: Server supports TLS configuration\n36: - **GIVEN** TLS certificate and key files specified in configuration\n37: - **WHEN** the operator starts the server with TLS enabled\n38: - **THEN** the server SHALL serve HTTPS using the provided certificates\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ### Requirement: Health and Readiness Endpoints\n43: \n44: The system SHALL expose standard Kubernetes health check endpoints for liveness and readiness probes.\n45: \n46: #### Scenario: Liveness endpoint returns healthy\n47: - **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager HTTP server is running\n48: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/healthz`\n49: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with body `{\"status\": \"ok\"}` when the process is alive\n50: \n51: #### Scenario: Readiness endpoint reflects dependency health\n52: - **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager has initialized all dependencies (Kubernetes client, Redis connection)\n53: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/readyz`\n54: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with body `{\"status\": \"ready\"}` when all dependencies are healthy\n55: \n56: #### Scenario: Readiness endpoint returns not ready\n57: - **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager has a failed dependency (e.g., Kubernetes API unreachable)\n58: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/readyz`\n59: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 503 with body `{\"status\": \"not_ready\", \"reason\": \"<failure_reason>\"}`\n60: \n61: #### Scenario: Health endpoint includes detailed checks\n62: - **GIVEN** the configuration enables verbose health checks\n63: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/healthz?verbose=true`\n64: - **THEN** the server SHALL return detailed health status for each registered health check component\n65: \n66: ---\n67: \n68: ### Requirement: RESTful API for AgentRuntime Resources\n69: \n70: The system SHALL expose RESTful HTTP endpoints for CRUD operations on AgentRuntime resources.\n71: \n72: #### Scenario: List AgentRuntimes\n73: - **GIVEN** AgentRuntime resources exist in namespace `default`\n74: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes`\n75: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with a JSON list of AgentRuntime objects\n76: \n77: #### Scenario: Get single AgentRuntime\n78: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime named `test-runtime` exists in namespace `default`\n79: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime`\n80: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with the AgentRuntime JSON object\n81: \n82: #### Scenario: Get non-existent AgentRuntime returns 404\n83: - **GIVEN** no AgentRuntime named `non-existent` exists in namespace `default`\n84: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/non-existent`\n85: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 404 with error details\n86: \n87: #### Scenario: Create AgentRuntime\n88: - **GIVEN** a valid AgentRuntime JSON payload\n89: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes` with the payload\n90: - **THEN** the server SHALL create the resource via Kubernetes API and return HTTP 201 with the created object\n91: \n92: #### Scenario: Create invalid AgentRuntime returns 400\n93: - **GIVEN** an invalid AgentRuntime JSON payload (missing required fields)\n94: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes` with the invalid payload\n95: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 with validation error details\n96: \n97: #### Scenario: Update AgentRuntime\n98: - **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime named `test-runtime`\n99: - **WHEN** a PUT request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime` with updated spec\n100: - **THEN** the server SHALL update the resource and return HTTP 200 with the updated object\n101: \n102: #### Scenario: Delete AgentRuntime\n103: - **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime named `test-runtime`\n104: - **WHEN** a DELETE request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime`\n105: - **THEN** the server SHALL delete the resource and return HTTP 200 with the deleted object\n106: \n107: #### Scenario: Watch AgentRuntimes\n108: - **GIVEN** the server supports streaming endpoints\n109: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes?watch=true`\n110: - **THEN** the server SHALL establish a streaming connection and emit ADDED/MODIFIED/DELETED events as resources change\n111: \n112: ---\n113: \n114: ### Requirement: RESTful API for CodeInterpreter Resources\n115: \n116: The system SHALL expose RESTful HTTP endpoints for CRUD operations on CodeInterpreter resources.\n117: \n118: #### Scenario: List CodeInterpreters\n119: - **GIVEN** CodeInterpreter resources exist in namespace `default`\n120: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters`\n121: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with a JSON list of CodeInterpreter objects\n122: \n123: #### Scenario: Get single CodeInterpreter\n124: - **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter named `test-interpreter` exists in namespace `default`\n125: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters/test-interpreter`\n126: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with the CodeInterpreter JSON object\n127: \n128: #### Scenario: Create CodeInterpreter\n129: - **GIVEN** a valid CodeInterpreter JSON payload\n130: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters` with the payload\n131: - **THEN** the server SHALL create the resource via Kubernetes API and return HTTP 201 with the created object\n132: \n133: #### Scenario: Update CodeInterpreter\n134: - **GIVEN** an existing CodeInterpreter named `test-interpreter`\n135: - **WHEN** a PUT request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters/test-interpreter` with updated spec\n136: - **THEN** the server SHALL update the resource and return HTTP 200 with the updated object\n137: \n138: #### Scenario: Delete CodeInterpreter\n139: - **GIVEN** an existing CodeInterpreter named `test-interpreter`\n140: - **WHEN** a DELETE request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters/test-interpreter`\n141: - **THEN** the server SHALL delete the resource and return HTTP 200 with the deleted object\n142: \n143: #### Scenario: Watch CodeInterpreters\n144: - **GIVEN** the server supports streaming endpoints\n145: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters?watch=true`\n146: - **THEN** the server SHALL establish a streaming connection and emit ADDED/MODIFIED/DELETED events as resources change\n147: \n148: ---\n149: \n150: ### Requirement: Resource Status Endpoints\n151: \n152: The system SHALL expose endpoints for retrieving and updating resource status.\n153: \n154: #### Scenario: Get AgentRuntime status\n155: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime named `test-runtime` exists with status information\n156: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime/status`\n157: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with only the status portion of the resource\n158: \n159: #### Scenario: Update AgentRuntime status\n160: - **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime named `test-runtime`\n161: - **WHEN** a PUT request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime/status` with new status\n162: - **THEN** the server SHALL update only the status subresource and return HTTP 200\n163: \n164: #### Scenario: Get CodeInterpreter status\n165: - **GIVEN** a CodeInterpreter named `test-interpreter` exists with status information\n166: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/codeinterpreters/test-interpreter/status`\n167: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with only the status portion of the resource\n168: \n169: ---\n170: \n171: ### Requirement: Kubernetes Client Integration\n172: \n173: The system SHALL integrate with the Kubernetes API using the generated client-go library.\n174: \n175: #### Scenario: Client initialization from in-cluster config\n176: - **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager is running inside a Kubernetes pod\n177: - **WHEN** the server initializes the Kubernetes client\n178: - **THEN** it SHALL use in-cluster configuration to connect to the Kubernetes API server\n179: \n180: #### Scenario: Client initialization from kubeconfig\n181: - **GIVEN** a valid kubeconfig file at `~/.kube/config` when running outside the cluster\n182: - **WHEN** the server initializes the Kubernetes client\n183: - **THEN** it SHALL use the kubeconfig to connect to the Kubernetes API server\n184: \n185: #### Scenario: Client uses typed clientset\n186: - **GIVEN** the Kubernetes client is initialized\n187: - **WHEN** the server handles AgentRuntime API requests\n188: - **THEN** it SHALL use the generated `clientset.Interface` from `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go`\n189: \n190: #### Scenario: Client handles authentication\n191: - **GIVEN** the service account has proper RBAC permissions\n192: - **WHEN** the server makes API requests\n193: - **THEN** the client SHALL authenticate using the service account token and certificate\n194: \n195: ---\n196: \n197: ### Requirement: Request Routing and Middleware\n198: \n199: The system SHALL implement HTTP request routing with middleware support for cross-cutting concerns.\n200: \n201: #### Scenario: Route registration\n202: - **GIVEN** the server is being configured\n203: - **WHEN** handlers are registered with the router\n204: - **THEN** each route SHALL be mapped to the correct HTTP method and path pattern\n205: \n206: #### Scenario: Request logging middleware\n207: - **GIVEN** a request is received by the server\n208: - **WHEN** the request is processed\n209: - **THEN** the server SHALL log the request method, path, status code, and duration\n210: \n211: #### Scenario: Request ID middleware\n212: - **GIVEN** a request is received without an `X-Request-ID` header\n213: - **WHEN** the request is processed\n214: - **THEN** the server SHALL generate a unique request ID and include it in response headers\n215: \n216: #### Scenario: CORS middleware\n217: - **GIVEN** CORS is enabled in configuration\n218: - **WHEN** a cross-origin request is received\n219: - **THEN** the server SHALL respond with appropriate CORS headers\n220: \n221: #### Scenario: Panic recovery middleware\n222: - **GIVEN** a request handler panics during execution\n223: - **WHEN** the request is processed\n224: - **THEN** the server SHALL recover from the panic, log the error, and return HTTP 500 without crashing\n225: \n226: #### Scenario: Authentication middleware\n227: - **GIVEN** authentication is enabled in configuration\n228: - **WHEN** a request is received without valid credentials\n229: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 401 Unauthorized\n230: \n231: ---\n232: \n233: ### Requirement: Request/Response Serialization\n234: \n235: The system SHALL properly serialize and deserialize JSON request and response bodies.\n236: \n237: #### Scenario: JSON request deserialization\n238: - **GIVEN** a POST request with `Content-Type: application/json`\n239: - **WHEN** the server receives the request body\n240: - **THEN** it SHALL deserialize the JSON into the appropriate Go struct\n241: \n242: #### Scenario: JSON response serialization\n243: - **GIVEN** a handler returns a Go struct\n244: - **WHEN** the server sends the response\n245: - **THEN** it SHALL serialize the struct to JSON with `Content-Type: application/json`\n246: \n247: #### Scenario: JSON field naming convention\n248: - **GIVEN** API response structs use camelCase JSON tags\n249: - **WHEN** responses are serialized\n250: - **THEN** field names SHALL follow camelCase convention (e.g., `createdAt`, `resourceVersion`)\n251: \n252: #### Scenario: Error response format\n253: - **GIVEN** an error occurs during request processing\n254: - **WHEN** the server returns an error response\n255: - **THEN** it SHALL return a JSON object with `error` and `message` fields (e.g., `{\"error\": \"NotFound\", \"message\": \"resource not found\"}`)\n256: \n257: ---\n258: \n259: ### Requirement: Query Parameter Support\n260: \n261: The system SHALL support standard Kubernetes-style query parameters for list operations.\n262: \n263: #### Scenario: Label selector filtering\n264: - **GIVEN** resources with various labels exist\n265: - **WHEN** a GET request is made with `?labelSelector=app=myapp`\n266: - **THEN** the server SHALL return only resources matching the label selector\n267: \n268: #### Scenario: Field selector filtering\n269: - **GIVEN** resources with various field values exist\n270: - **WHEN** a GET request is made with `?fieldSelector=spec.image=myimage`\n271: - **THEN** the server SHALL return only resources matching the field selector\n272: \n273: #### Scenario: Pagination with limit and continue\n274: - **GIVEN** more than 100 resources exist\n275: - **WHEN** a GET request is made with `?limit=10`\n276: - **THEN** the server SHALL return at most 10 items and include a `continue` token for pagination\n277: \n278: #### Scenario: Watch with resource version\n279: - **GIVEN** resources exist at resource version `12345`\n280: - **WHEN** a GET request is made with `?watch=true&resourceVersion=12345`\n281: - **THEN** the server SHALL start the watch from that resource version\n282: \n283: ---\n284: \n285: ### Requirement: Metrics and Observability\n286: \n287: The system SHALL expose Prometheus metrics for monitoring HTTP server performance.\n288: \n289: #### Scenario: HTTP request metrics\n290: - **GIVEN** the server is handling requests\n291: - **WHEN** metrics endpoint `/metrics` is scraped\n292: - **THEN** it SHALL expose `http_requests_total` counter with labels for method, path, and status\n293: \n294: #### Scenario: HTTP request duration metrics\n295: - **GIVEN** the server is handling requests\n296: - **WHEN** metrics endpoint `/metrics` is scraped\n297: - **THEN** it SHALL expose `http_request_duration_seconds` histogram with labels for method and path\n298: \n299: #### Scenario: Kubernetes client metrics\n300: - **GIVEN** the server is making Kubernetes API calls\n301: - **WHEN** metrics endpoint `/metrics` is scraped\n302: - **THEN** it SHALL expose `kubernetes_client_requests_total` counter for API operations\n303: \n304: #### Scenario: Resource operation metrics\n305: - **GIVEN** the server is processing AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter operations\n306: - **WHEN** metrics endpoint `/metrics` is scraped\n307: - **THEN** it SHALL expose counters for create/update/delete operations by resource type\n308: \n309: ---\n310: \n311: ### Requirement: Structured Logging\n312: \n313: The system SHALL implement structured logging for all operations.\n314: \n315: #### Scenario: Request logging with fields\n316: - **GIVEN** a request is processed\n317: - **WHEN** the server logs the request\n318: - **THEN** it SHALL include structured fields: `method`, `path`, `status`, `duration`, `request_id`\n319: \n320: #### Scenario: Error logging with context\n321: - **GIVEN** an error occurs during API processing\n322: - **WHEN** the error is logged\n323: - **THEN** it SHALL include structured fields: `error`, `resource_type`, `resource_name`, `namespace`, `request_id`\n324: \n325: #### Scenario: Kubernetes API logging\n326: - **GIVEN** the server makes a Kubernetes API call\n327: - **WHEN** the operation is logged\n328: - **THEN** it SHALL include fields: `operation`, `resource`, `namespace`, `duration`, `error` (if any)\n329: \n330: #### Scenario: Configurable log level\n331: - **GIVEN** the `LOG_LEVEL` environment variable is set to `debug`\n332: - **WHEN** the server logs messages\n333: - **THEN** debug-level messages SHALL be output alongside info and error messages\n334: \n335: ---\n336: \n337: ### Requirement: Configuration Management\n338: \n339: The system SHALL support configuration via environment variables and configuration files.\n340: \n341: #### Scenario: Server configuration from environment variables\n342: - **GIVEN** environment variables `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_HOST`, `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_PORT`, `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_TLS_CERT`, `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_TLS_KEY`\n343: - **WHEN** the configuration is loaded\n344: - **THEN** it SHALL populate the server configuration struct with these values\n345: \n346: #### Scenario: Kubernetes configuration from environment\n347: - **GIVEN** environment variables `KUBECONFIG` or in-cluster configuration\n348: - **WHEN** the Kubernetes client configuration is loaded\n349: - **THEN** it SHALL use the specified kubeconfig or in-cluster settings\n350: \n351: #### Scenario: Redis configuration from environment\n352: - **GIVEN** environment variables `REDIS_ADDR` and `REDIS_PASSWORD`\n353: - **WHEN** the Redis client configuration is loaded\n354: - **THEN** it SHALL populate the Redis connection configuration\n355: \n356: #### Scenario: Configuration validation\n357: - **GIVEN** an invalid configuration (e.g., invalid port number)\n358: - **WHEN** the configuration is loaded\n359: - **THEN** it SHALL return a validation error before starting the server\n360: \n361: ---\n362: \n363: ### Requirement: Error Handling\n364: \n365: The system SHALL implement consistent error handling across all endpoints.\n366: \n367: #### Scenario: Kubernetes API errors mapped to HTTP status\n368: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes API call returns `apierrors.IsNotFound`\n369: - **WHEN** the error is processed\n370: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 404\n371: \n372: #### Scenario: Kubernetes API conflict mapped to HTTP 409\n373: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes API call returns `apierrors.IsConflict`\n374: - **WHEN** the error is processed\n375: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 409 Conflict\n376: \n377: #### Scenario: Kubernetes API unauthorized mapped to HTTP 403\n378: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes API call returns `apierrors.IsForbidden`\n379: - **WHEN** the error is processed\n380: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 403 Forbidden\n381: \n382: #### Scenario: Internal server errors mapped to HTTP 500\n383: - **GIVEN** an unexpected internal error occurs\n384: - **WHEN** the error is processed\n385: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 500 with a generic error message (details logged but not exposed)\n386: \n387: #### Scenario: Validation errors mapped to HTTP 400\n388: - **GIVEN** a request fails validation\n389: - **WHEN** the error is processed\n390: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 Bad Request with validation error details\n391: \n392: ---\n393: \n394: ### Requirement: Server Command Line Interface\n395: \n396: The system SHALL provide a CLI entry point for starting the WorkloadManager server.\n397: \n398: #### Scenario: Server starts with default configuration\n399: - **GIVEN** the `workloadmanager` binary is built\n400: - **WHEN** the operator runs `./bin/workloadmanager server`\n401: - **THEN** the server SHALL start with default configuration values\n402: \n403: #### Scenario: Server starts with flags\n404: - **GIVEN** command-line flags `--host=0.0.0.0 --port=9090 --tls-cert=/cert.pem --tls-key=/key.pem`\n405: - **WHEN** the operator runs `./bin/workloadmanager server` with these flags\n406: - **THEN** the server SHALL start with the specified configuration\n407: \n408: #### Scenario: Server shows help\n409: - **GIVEN** the operator wants to see available options\n410: - **WHEN** the operator runs `./bin/workloadmanager server --help`\n411: - **THEN** it SHALL display help text with all available flags and their descriptions\n412: \n413: #### Scenario: Server respects signal handling\n414: - **GIVEN** the server is running\n415: - **WHEN** the process receives SIGTERM or SIGINT\n416: - **THEN** the server SHALL initiate graceful shutdown with a configurable timeout\n417: \n418: ---\n419: \n420: ## File Index\n421: \n422: | Path | Purpose |\n423: |------|---------|\n424: | `cmd/workload-manager/main.go` | Main entry point for the WorkloadManager binary |\n425: | `pkg/workloadmanager/server/server.go` | HTTP server bootstrap and lifecycle management |\n426: | `pkg/workloadmanager/server/config.go` | Server configuration structures and loading |\n427: | `pkg/workloadmanager/server/routes.go` | HTTP route definitions and handler registration |\n428: | `pkg/workloadmanager/server/middleware.go` | HTTP middleware implementations (logging, recovery, auth) |\n429: | `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/health.go` | Health and readiness endpoint handlers |\n430: | `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/agentruntime.go` | AgentRuntime CRUD endpoint handlers |\n431: | `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/codeinterpreter.go` | CodeInterpreter CRUD endpoint handlers |\n432: | `pkg/workloadmanager/handlers/common.go` | Common handler utilities and response helpers |\n433: | `pkg/workloadmanager/client/kube.go` | Kubernetes client initialization and wrapper |\n434: | `pkg/workloadmanager/metrics/metrics.go` | Prometheus metrics definitions and recording |\n435: | `pkg/workloadmanager/logger/logger.go` | Structured logging configuration and helpers |\n436: \n437: ---\n438: \n439: ## Dependencies\n440: \n441: | Dependency | Version | Purpose |\n442: |------------|---------|---------|\n443: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go` | Local | Generated Kubernetes clientset |\n444: | `k8s.io/client-go` | `v0.34.1` | Kubernetes REST client |\n445: | `k8s.io/apimachinery` | `v0.34.1` | Kubernetes API machinery |\n446: | `github.com/gorilla/mux` or `net/http` | Latest | HTTP routing |\n447: | `github.com/prometheus/client_golang` | Latest | Prometheus metrics |\n448: | `github.com/sirupsen/logrus` or `slog` | Latest | Structured logging |\n449: | `github.com/rs/cors` | Latest | CORS middleware (optional) |\n450: \n451: ---\n452: \n453: ## API Endpoints Summary\n454: \n455: | Method | Path | Description |\n456: |--------|------|-------------|\n457: | GET | `/healthz` | Liveness probe |\n458: | GET | `/readyz` | Readiness probe |\n459: | GET | `/metrics` | Prometheus metrics |\n460: | GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes` | List AgentRuntimes |\n461: | POST | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes` | Create AgentRuntime |\n462: | GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes/{name}` | Get AgentRuntime |\n463: | PUT | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes/{name}` | Update AgentRuntime |\n464: | DELETE | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes/{name}` | Delete AgentRuntime |\n465: | GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes/{name}/status` | Get AgentRuntime status |\n466: | PUT | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agentruntimes/{name}/status` | Update AgentRuntime status |\n467: | GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters` | List CodeInterpreters |\n468: | POST | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters` | Create CodeInterpreter |\n469: | GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters/{name}` | Get CodeInterpreter |\n470: | PUT | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters/{name}` | Update CodeInterpreter |\n471: | DELETE | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters/{name}` | Delete CodeInterpreter |\n472: | GET | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters/{name}/status` | Get CodeInterpreter status |\n473: | PUT | `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/codeinterpreters/{name}/status` | Update CodeInterpreter status |\n474: \n475: ---\n476: \n477: ## Notes\n478: \n479: - The WorkloadManager HTTP service serves as the control plane API for the AgentCube system\n480: - All endpoints that modify resources SHALL use the Kubernetes API server for persistence\n481: - The service SHALL be stateless, with all state stored in Kubernetes resources and Redis\n482: - The API follows RESTful conventions similar to the Kubernetes API for consistency\n483: - WebSocket or Server-Sent Events (SSE) may be used for the watch endpoints\n484: - The service SHALL support both in-cluster and external Kubernetes cluster configurations\n\n(End of file - total 484 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Spec: AR-004 — WorkloadManager HTTP Service Framework\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-004  \n**Module:** pkg/workloadmanager  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n\nEstablish the HTTP service framework for the WorkloadManager component, providing RESTful APIs for managing AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources, health endpoints, and integration with the Kubernetes client-go library.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: HTTP Server Bootstrap\n\nThe system SHALL provide a configurable HTTP server that can be started and gracefully shut down.\n\n#### Scenario: Server starts with configuration","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775848440797,"end":1775848440826}}}}
